      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Read a Queensland Contract of Sale: Key Clauses Every Seller Must Understand
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The contract of sale is the document your sale lives or dies on. Knowing which clauses matter most and why protects you before you sign.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers never read their contract of sale carefully. They rely on their agent to explain it and their solicitor to flag anything unusual. That approach is not entirely wrong, but it leaves sellers dependent on other people for decisions that are fundamentally theirs to make. Understanding the key clauses in your contract before you receive an offer gives you context you need to negotiate effectively and avoid agreeing to terms that can create problems later in the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the REIQ/ADL contract is and why it is used</h2>
      <p>The standard form contract used for residential property sales in Queensland is a joint publication of the Real Estate Institute of Queensland and the ADL. It is not a government document, though it operates within the framework of Queensland's property legislation, including the Property Law Act 1974 and the Property Occupations Act 2014. The standard contract is used almost universally for private treaty sales in Queensland because it provides a well-understood template that solicitors, agents, buyers, and sellers all recognise.</p>

      <p>The contract is standard in structure but not fixed in terms. Both buyers and sellers can add special conditions that modify the standard clauses. Understanding the standard conditions first makes it easier to evaluate what any special conditions are trying to achieve.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Purchase price and deposit terms</h2>
      <p>The front page of the contract records the purchase price, the deposit amount, how and when the deposit is to be paid, and who holds it. In Queensland, the deposit is typically 10% of the purchase price, though 5% is common for buyers with tighter finances and acceptable to many sellers if the buyer's position is otherwise strong. The deposit is generally held in a trust account by the real estate agent until settlement.</p>

      <p>Sellers should pay attention to the timing of the deposit payment. The standard contract requires the deposit to be paid within a specified number of days of the contract date, or on the satisfaction of conditions, depending on how the contract is structured. An uncashed or delayed deposit is a signal worth querying before the contract becomes unconditional.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The finance condition</h2>
      <p>If the buyer requires finance, the contract will include a finance condition that gives them a specified number of days to obtain formal loan approval. During this period, the contract is conditional: either party may have rights to terminate if the condition is not met, depending on the exact wording.</p>

      <p>Typical finance periods in Queensland run from 14 to 21 days. From a seller's perspective, a shorter finance period is preferable because it reduces the time the property is effectively off the market while the buyer arranges their loan. However, pushing for an unrealistically short period can lead to the buyer failing to get formal approval in time and the contract collapsing, which is worse than a slightly longer conditional period. The right finance period depends on the buyer's loan type and lender, and your agent should be able to advise based on the specific buyer's circumstances.</p>

      <p>Finance conditions can be drafted in different ways. Some require the buyer to make reasonable efforts to obtain finance; others simply require formal approval by the finance date. The distinction matters if the buyer fails to get approval and you are trying to determine whether you can keep the deposit. Your solicitor can advise on the specific wording in your contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The building and pest condition</h2>
      <p>The building and pest condition gives the buyer the right to have the property inspected by a licensed building inspector and pest inspector during a specified period, typically 7 to 14 days from the contract date. The buyer bears the cost of those inspections.</p>

      <p>If the inspections reveal defects, what happens next depends on how the condition is drafted. Some building and pest conditions allow the buyer to terminate for any reason; others only allow termination if defects exceed a certain cost threshold or meet a specific definition of structural defect. Standard REIQ contracts typically allow buyers to terminate if an inspection reveals defects that are not minor.</p>

      <p>Sellers in Brisbane's inner east who own character homes, Queenslanders, or pre-1980s dwellings should expect building and pest conditions in most offers. Older properties with high ceilings, timber frames, and extensive subfloor areas tend to attract more detailed inspection reports. Being aware of any significant defects in your property before you list, and either addressing them or pricing accordingly, puts you in a stronger position during the building and pest period rather than a reactive one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The settlement date clause</h2>
      <p>The settlement date is the date on which ownership transfers and you receive your proceeds. In Queensland, settlement typically occurs 30 to 60 days after the contract date, though shorter or longer periods can be agreed. What is standard varies: 30 days is common for vacant or investment properties; 45 to 60 days is more typical where the seller needs time to find and move to their next property.</p>

      <p>The settlement date is one of the most negotiable clauses in the contract from both sides. Sellers with flexibility on settlement timing can sometimes attract stronger offers by accommodating the buyer's preferred date. If you need a longer settlement to coordinate your own purchase, make that clear to your agent before marketing begins so offers can be invited on that basis.</p>

      <p>Extensions to settlement are common and do not necessarily indicate a problem with the buyer. However, a buyer who requests multiple extensions without a clear explanation is a warning sign worth discussing with your solicitor before agreeing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pool safety compliance</h2>
      <p>Queensland has mandatory pool safety requirements under the Building Act 1975 and associated regulations. Sellers are required to provide buyers with either a current pool safety certificate issued by a licensed pool safety inspector, or a notice of no pool safety certificate. If you provide a notice of no pool safety certificate, the buyer takes on the obligation to obtain a certificate within 90 days of settlement.</p>

      <p>The contract records which approach applies to your property. Most sellers of owner-occupied properties prefer to obtain the certificate before selling, as it removes any uncertainty about pool compliance from the buyer's perspective and reduces the likelihood of it becoming a negotiating point. Pool safety certificates are valid for 2 years for non-shared pools and 1 year for shared pools in residential properties. If your certificate is current, check the expiry date to confirm it will still be valid at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Smoke alarm compliance</h2>
      <p>Queensland's smoke alarm legislation (under the Fire and Emergency Services Act 1990, as amended) requires all residential properties sold after 1 January 2022 to have interconnected photoelectric smoke alarms installed in required locations. Sellers must certify compliance in the contract.</p>

      <p>If your property does not yet meet the current requirements, you will need to upgrade the alarms before or at settlement. The cost of compliance is relatively low compared to the risk of certifying compliance incorrectly. If you are not sure whether your property meets the current requirements, your agent or a licensed electrician can advise. This is one compliance item where sellers sometimes underestimate the scope of the upgrade required.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The chattels and inclusions schedule</h2>
      <p>The contract includes a schedule that specifies what stays with the property and what leaves with the seller. Fixtures are generally included in the sale (items that are permanently attached to the property), while chattels are generally excluded (items that are freestanding or easily removable). The line between fixture and chattel is often clear, but not always.</p>

      <p>Light fittings, built-in shelving, dishwashers, and ducted air conditioning units are typically treated as fixtures included in the sale unless the contract specifies otherwise. Freestanding fridges, curtains, pot plants, and garden sheds on skids are typically excluded unless specifically listed as included. Disputes over inclusions are one of the most preventable sources of post-contract friction. If you intend to take something with you, note it in the contract as excluded. If a buyer asks that something specific be included, confirm it in the contract rather than relying on verbal agreement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Special conditions: what they are and what to watch for</h2>
      <p>Special conditions are additions to the standard contract that modify the standard terms or add obligations not otherwise present. They can be initiated by the buyer or the seller. Common buyer-initiated special conditions include making the purchase subject to the sale of the buyer's existing property, early access to the property before settlement, or retaining the right to conduct additional inspections. Common seller-initiated special conditions include requiring the buyer to accept the property in an as-is condition for specific items, or specifying that certain items are excluded from the sale.</p>

      <p>Not all special conditions are unreasonable, but some shift significant risk onto the seller in ways that are not immediately obvious. A condition that makes the contract subject to the buyer's existing property selling, with no sunset date, effectively means you have accepted an offer with no certainty of completion and have taken your property off the market. A condition that allows the buyer broad rights to terminate for vague reasons similarly reduces the security of your contract. Your solicitor should review any special conditions before you accept an offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Have your own solicitor review the contract</h2>
      <p>Your agent can explain what the contract says. Your agent cannot give you legal advice about what it means for you, and should not be relied on as a substitute for a solicitor. The cost of having a Queensland conveyancing solicitor review your contract before you sign is modest relative to the value of the transaction, and it is the only way to get advice that is specifically yours rather than generally applicable.</p>

      <p>This is particularly important if you receive an offer with non-standard terms, if the buyer is purchasing through a company or trust structure, or if the property has any complications such as an easement, a covenant, unregistered works, or a tenancy that needs to end before settlement. Your agent can refer you to a conveyancing solicitor if you do not already have one.</p>

